(1, 'Taking the TERRIBLE out of the TWOS!', '34bf9a1541fd8fd7d19375afac539b29.jpg', '<p><strong><span style="font-size:18px">Having worked as a career nanny for 15 years, I don&#39;t understand the label </span></strong><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="font-size:18px">&#39;terrible twos&#39;.</span></strong> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Personally, its my favourite age group to care for. They are exploring their environments to develop knowledge and life skills, yet remain so innocent and vulnerable.<span style="color:#0000FF"> Its an enormous year of learning and growing,</span> when their little personalities develop and explode. How these personalities develop can be largely influenced by the caregivers in their world...whether it be the mum, dad, grandma, nanny or anyone involved in their upbringing. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">They are very quick to learn the limitations implemented by different carers. <span style="color:#ff0099">It all about &#39;cause and effect&#39;</span>. Therefore, how the adults respond, encourage and role model behaviours will have a massive impact on their level of TERRIBLE! </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#0000CD"><strong>1. Set limits.</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> By setting limits, the toddler knows what they can and can&#39;t do, so by giving them clear boundaries you can reduce the amount of &#39;NOs. Let them know what actions are appropriate rather than constantly reprimanding them for those which are not. &#39; Their little brains are like sponges soaking up data. Even if your toddler isn&#39;t saying many words yet, their receptive language skills are better than you may think.Try to reinforce these limits with positivity rather than negativity. For example, &quot;you must hold my hand near the road to stay safe&quot; over &quot;don&#39;t let go of my hand or you&#39;ll be run over&quot;.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#0000CD"><strong>2. Provide a safe environment </strong></span></span><span style="font-size:14px">. Prevention is always better than cure. Less accidents, means less tears and less upset for everyone involved. Keep dangerous objects out of harms reach. Provide areas that promote independence without sacrificing their safety. Let them have little bins and falls to learn about their own capabilities and provide praise for any newly mastered skills. Expose them to stairs they can master, store dangerous products out of reach and give them more than one safe place to explore.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#0000CD"><strong>3.Stay consistent.</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> Give in once, and you have given in a thousand times! &quot;But its easier just to give in sometimes&quot;. This is the biggest of them all. Yes, there are times when we adults are tired and can&#39;t be bothered with &#39;the fight&#39;, but unfortunately short term gain from giving in, will result in long term pain of arguments. Don&#39;t make a threat that you&#39;re not prepared to carry through, or next time this same threat will be useless. If you threatened to leave the park if unsavoury behaviour continues, and it does persist...leave the park! Next time, your toddler will know you mean it. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>4.Role model appropriate behaviour. </strong></span></span><span style="font-size:14px">You may as well throw the saying out the door &quot;do as I say and not as I do&quot;, if you&#39;re hoping for a terrific two. Children look up to their carers and want to be just like them. Don&#39;t leave your dirty washing laying all over the bedroom floor and then expect the toddler to pack up their toys. They believe everything you say and have faith in everything you do. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><strong><span style="color:#0000CD">5. Know their developmental capabilities</span></strong></span><span style="font-size:14px">. Temper tantrums are a normal aspect of development for toddlers, but if they are not handled correctly, they will be longer and louder than anyone cares to imagine. 2 year old tantrums are mostly an expression of their emotions. They usually don&#39;t have the expressive language skills to logically express what they are feeling. Try to ignore tantrums as best you can. Make sure the child is in a safe area where you can see them and let them cry it out...... but don&#39;t give attention and don&#39;t give in! There is an abundance of information on the web related to child development. </span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:18px">6. Give praise for positive behaviour over focusing on the negative.</span></span></strong><span style="font-size:14px"> But do this carefully, as overuse can be like water off a ducks back. Praise the behaviour where its earnt and don&#39;t put too much attention about the less favourable actions. Chance are, the negative behaviour is attention seeking, and if they don&#39;t get any attention for it, they quickly realise it doesn&#39;t work. 6 Know the triggers. Take a mental and/or written note of particularly traumatic situations to gather any patterns which can indicate triggers. Some examples of triggers can be tiredness, hunger, frustration, reaction to certain foods or just plain attention seeking. A good routine can usually rule out tiredness and hunger, a healthy diet can limit food preservative triggers and providing developmentally appropriate activities covers a lot of frustration. As far as attention seeking behaviour, remember to give no attention to negative behaviour. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><strong><span style="color:#0000CD">7.Time out still remains a debatable form of discipline.</span></strong></span><span style="font-size:14px"> If you choose to use it, make sure the time-out area is free from activity, especially activity pleasurable to the child. Explain to the child why they have been put there and leave them for a couple of minutes to think about it. If they have impacted negatively on another child, encourage them to say &quot;sorry&quot;. Toddlers are egocentric and they won&#39;t mean sorry even if they say it, but it installs good manners for the future. If the child bluntly refuses to apologise, don&#39;t make a huge deal out of it. Simply apologise on their behalf, tell them that your disappointed and leave the situation. </span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#0000CD">8.Provide choice.</span></span></strong><span style="font-size:14px"> Young children like to make decisions to feel in control. Offer them choices that are realistic and don&#39;t leave them too open or you may not agree with their choice. For example, at dinner time, don&#39;t ask them &quot;what do you want for dinner?&quot; but instead ask &quot;would you like pasta or chicken for dinner?&quot; </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>9. Remain calm.</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> Yelling won&#39;t help yelling. If a child is constantly yelled at, it becomes their norm. Remain calm, get down to their eye level and express your disappointment in a level voice. </span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#0000CD">10. Don&#39;t be scared of upsetting your child.</span></span></strong><span style="font-size:14px"> If you implement all the above, chances are, your terrible two year old will be mostly terrific. If your child becomes upset from discipline, don&#39;t worry, its healthy for them to have a good cry and they won&#39;t love you any less.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#ff0099">EVERY CHILD IS UNIQUE...BUT THESE PRINCIPALS HAVE BEEN SUCCESSFUL IN EVERY SINGLE CHILD I HAVE CARED FOR IN THE PAST 15</span> <span style="color:#ff0099">YEARS.</span> And remember, just because its known as the terrible twos...it can start at 12months and will continue for as long as you allow it. </span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:14px">Good luck and enjoy them.........&nbsp;<img alt="laugh" src="http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au/assets/js/ckeditor/plugins/smiley/images/teeth_smile.png" style="height:23px; width:23px" title="laugh" />&nbsp;Nanny Share Australia&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\n', 'taking-the-terrible-out-of-the-twos', '11/09/2014'),
(2, '"I WANT A NANNY!!!"', 'd84436ef678ec77d73d7421fcea515e2.jpg', ' My name is Amy.\nI am 6 months old.\nI live on Sydneys'' North Shore with my dad, mum and baby-on-the-way.\nMy dad is a builder.\nMy mum works in admin.\nOur rent is very high, as is the cost of living. My mum must return to work soon.\n\n\nOn her first day back at work she was really stressed. She woke me earlier than usual. It was cold and raining outside. She packed a bag for me, then battled  the weather to strap me into the car seat for a new adventure.\n\nFifteen minutes later, we arrived at a huge building that I had not seen before. There was a combination of laughter and tears coming from within. We entered a series of doors and safety procedures. I could see an abundance of toys and many unfamiliar faces. This place could be fun I thought. Then my mum handed me over to a stranger, kissed me softly and waved goodbye.\nWhat was happening? What is this place? Who are these people? Where is someone, or at least something, that''s familiar to me? How long will I have to stay in this strange place?\n\nEight hours later, my mum returned. Thank goodness she is back, I''ve felt quite uneasy all day. I hope she doesn''t need to leave me here again.\n\nThe next day, history repeats itself. We are back in this unfamiliar environment. This time, I knows she''s leaving so I''m upset before she does. I''m at the height of separation anxiety and I''m scared.\n\nFour weeks later, we are still going to this place. My upset begins as we pull up out the front. There are so may different faces for me to recognise. I''m not always greeted by the same carer. Although I have happy moments during the day, I mostly don''t like coming to this strange place. I don''t really like the food they are serving me. I don''t sleep very well in the cot room. Sometimes when I''m upset, no-one is immediately available to comfort me. \n\n There are lots of other children here whom seem to love it, but its just not for me.\n\nMy immune system isn''t coping with the exposure to all these germs. I always getting sick. Mum and dad are constantly arguing over who can stay home and care for me when I''m unwell.\n\nMy mum and dad really want to hire a nanny so I can be cared for at home. This way, I have a familiar face greeting me every day. I can spend a lot of time in my home environment. We don''t have to go out in the rain. I can sleep in my own room. And my nanny can cook pumpkin soup just the way I like it!\n\n"But we can''t afford a nanny", I hear my dad say. And this is where ''nanny share'' came to my rescue. If we share a nanny with a local family, we can split the cost, hence make it affordable.\n\n Now when my mum leaves for work, my nanny comes to my home. I see her 4 days a week so I get to know her well in a short period of time. My nanny loves me very much. I love the fact that I can spend my younger years being cared for at home. We also go on lots of little outings to parks and playgroups. \n\nThe other family involved in our nanny share agreement has a boy named Tom who is around the same age as me.  Sometimes Toms'' mum drops him off at our house for the day. Sometimes my mum takes me to Toms house for the day. I like going to Toms house. Tom has become my best friend. His house is like a second home to me. I love my nanny. I''m so glad my parents discovered  nanny share  and didn''t just brush off the idea of hiring a nanny under the assumption it was unaffordable!\n\nMy mum seems much happier going to work and leaving me in the care of a qualified, experienced nanny. My parents don''t argue about giving up work wen I''m sick because my nanny comes to care for me. I don''t get sick as often anymore. My nanny cooks nutritious meals for me and my parents, and sorts out my washing so my mum doesn''t have to worry about that on the weekends.  When my new sibling arrives, my nanny will care for them too for a little bit extra per hour. \n\nNanny Share..............the affordable option!!', 'i-want-a-nanny', '11/17/2014'),
(3, 'What is nanny share?', 'f3302cdbc10e09d34746e1456311ded4.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:22px"><span style="color:#ff0099"><strong>&quot;The who, what, when, where, why and how of nanny share&quot; WHO is nanny share for?</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Nanny share arrangements are perfect for families who wish to have their child cared for by a<span style="color:#0000CD"> nanny in their home environment, without the high price tag </span>. Sole charge nannies can cost as much as $300 per day. <span style="color:#0000CD">Nanny Share arrangements can be as low as $120</span> per day depending on your needs.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#ff0099">Who is nanny sharing for?</span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> Nanny sharing provides ongoing social stimulation for single-child families. <span style="color:#000000">If you want your child to be cared for in a home setting, even when they are unwell, and exposed to their local surroundings, then nanny share is for you. Ideally, families match well with other families who live locally and have a child of similar age </span>and/or routine. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#ff0099">WHAT is nanny share?</span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> Nanny share is exactly what is sounds like. An agreement whereby two families hire one nanny to care for their children together at the same time. In some instances, the nanny will care for the children of both families for an equal amount of time. In other cases, the nanny may have one primary family where the majority of her hours are worked, with the addition of care of a child from another family for a proportion of the week or day. Nanny share should not be confused with a sole charge nanny who splits her time. For example, in 1 day, the nanny works 7-11am for one family, then 11-6 for another...THIS IS NOT NANNY SHARE. If the nanny works 7-6 for family 1, then family 2 drops their child to her from 8-5, the hours of 8-5 are paid at the nanny share rate. The nanny is employed under one umbrella agreement with schedules tailored to meet everyone needs. Sometimes an agreement can include a third family if logistics are managed well. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#ff0099">When should I start looking at nanny share? </span></span><span style="font-size:14px">Babies can be placed in nanny share from as young as 6 weeks. Unlike day care centres, theres no lengthy waiting lists and ongoing stress of non-placement. You can start looking for a family to share with as soon as your baby is born. Its crucial to select the right family match, so the longer you look the more chance you have of finding the best match.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#ff0099">Where does nanny care take place?</span></span> <span style="font-size:14px">There are 3 options for this. Scenario 1, the care takes place at the home of family 1. Scenario 2, the care takes place at the home of family 2. Scenario 3, the care takes place in both homes alternatively each week. This is to be agreed upon by the families and nanny involved before any&nbsp;contract of employment commences.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:20px"><span style="color:#ff0099">Why choose nanny share?</span></span><span style="font-size:14px"> In a nutshell, because its the most cost effective way of having your child cared for by a nanny. Because the care is shared, so to is the cost! Some centres in Sydney charge as much as $170 per day. Quality day care places are becoming increasingly unavailable, whereas nanny share is becoming a growing trend. More and more families are understanding the benefits of nanny share, hence increasing the number of available families to share with. Your childs routine is managed individually by the nanny, they have one primary caregiver to alleviate the stress of separation anxiety, and the nanny will care for your little one when he or she is unwell. No more rushing out the door for day care drop offs, wait for your nanny to come to you! Nanny Share provides flexibility, close adult to child interactions and all round quality care at an affordable price.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><span style="color:#ff0099">How to find a successful nanny share arrangement?</span></span> <span style="font-size:14px">Nanny Share Australia is a new website assisting families all over Australia to find suitable family and/or nanny matches. You may prefer to use an agency to help you with your search, but be aware of high placement fees. <span style="color:#FF0000">Nanny Share Australia is free</span> <span style="color:#FF0000">to join so jump on and register your details now</span>. You can search at your own leisure and carry out the same background checks as any agency can do.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:22px"><a href="http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au"><span style="color:#0000CD">http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au</span></a></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px">NANNY SHARING......THE FUTURE OF QUALITY CHILD CARE!</span></span></p>\n', 'what-is-nanny-share', '11/26/2014'),
(4, 'How to choose the right nanny for a nanny share arrangement', '5792b4a195213538539430a856663a17.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#800080">When first embarking on the idea of nanny share, you may find some families already have a nanny. </span>If this is the case, its important to meet their nanny in an informal interview situation to decide if you think they are suitable to carry out the arrangement. Don&#39;t simply trust the opinion of the other family as it may result in future problems. <strong>It is crucial that both families are engaged in the process of choosing the right nanny.</strong> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Ideally, ask the nanny to meet all members of both families in the home or homes, where care will take place. The nanny should arrive at the interview with her CV which includes evidence of past employment, qualifications and certificates, and a list of references. A professional nanny will have a copy for you to keep. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Arrange the interview at a time when the children can be present. <strong>Take note of how the nanny interacts with your children</strong> during this time. Sometimes even young babies can be the judge of a misfit. First and foremost, the <strong>nanny must be the perfect fit for both families. </strong>Having worked as a nanny for 15 years myself, its usually evident after one meeting if there is a connection or not. Human nature is excellent at deciding this subconsciously. No amount of experience or qualifications can outweigh a clash in personalities. <strong>There needs to be similar values, ideas and beliefs between the families and the nanny for success to occur.</strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Keep interviewing until you feel 100% confident that you have found the perfect match for everyone involved. Ask yourself and the shared family what is most important for them in a nanny. <span style="color:#B22222">Reference checking cannot be stressed enough.</span> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Ideally, your nanny should provide you with contact details of at least 3 previous positions. Be sure to contact these references, asking everything about the nanny from their sense of humour and punctuality through to their standard of caring for children and any negative habits or behaviour that they displayed. <span style="color:#0000CD">Ask to see evidence of first aid certificates, qualifications and and relevant working with children checks.</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222">Below is a list of questions you may like to ask prospective nannies in the interview to help decide if they are the right fit for your family. Not all questions may be relevant to you individual needs. Remember to be as thorough as possible in the interview process. There&#39;s no such thing as a silly question! </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How long have you worked as a nanny?</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Why did you choose to become a nanny?</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What do you enjoy most about working as a nanny? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What do you enjoy least about working as a nanny?</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How long did you work in your longest position? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What age children do you prefer to care for and why? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Why did you previous positions end or change? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you looking for a long term commitment? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">When are you available to start? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Tell me about your typical day as a nanny in previous roles. </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What kind of activities do you do with children similar in age to ours? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are comfortable with driving children in your car, or a car provided? Do you have a good driving record? Can you drive manual? Do you have properly installed car seats? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have experience with twins and/or multiple children? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Have you ever worked in nanny share arrangement before, and if so, what were the positives and negatives of the arrangement? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What qualifications do you have?How do you use you qualifications in everyday nannying situations? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What methods of communication have you used between you and the families? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you first aid trained and have you dealt with an emergency situation in the past? Have you ever had to deal with a choking incident? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have experience with any children with special needs or food allergies? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What are your views towards healthy eating? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How would you approach any challenging issues with the families? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you a competent swimmer and do you feel comfortable swimming with multiple children? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What methods of discipline do you usually enforce? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How flexible are you with working hours, are you happy to start earlier or finish later if the need arises? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you prepared to carry out household duties such as cooking and washing? Are than any duties or activities that you are not prepared to carry out? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have any other special skills that would be advantageous to hiring you as our nanny. e.g., speak a second language, play a musical instrument, trained in sleep guidance </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How do you handle separation anxiety and sleep settling? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you prepared to work for a third family if the situation arises? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">What is your hourly rate? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have an ABN? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you smoke? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you comfortable with pets? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Are you happy to take the children to organised activities? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">How will you encourage social skills with my child? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Can you cook? And are you willing to cook the family meal?</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have any pre-booked holidays planned in the near future? How have you organised holidays with past families? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have the relevant checks for working with children? In NSW, nannies should have a Working with children check certificate which can be shown on request. Some may also possess a police check. </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Don&#39;t be afraid to ask anything that you feel is relevant. The more you ask, the more knowledge you have to make the best possible choice. Consistency is so important for your children, so choose carefully and be sure to cover all bases. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Remember to REFERENCE CHECK thoroughly. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">HAPPY NANNY SHARE!</span></p>\n', 'how-to-choose-the-right-nanny-for-a-nanny-share-arrangement', '2014-11-30'),
(5, 'How much should i expect to pay a shared nanny?', '1b0681a32defa3c4192994d590214a2b.jpg', '<p><span style="color:#800080"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>HOW MUCH WILL A NANNY SHARE COST?</strong></span> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Probably the most commonly asked question from families considering nanny share, and the most decisive answer as to whether or not it is suitable for you and your family. Unfortunately, the nanny industry remains de-regulated in Australia, which makes it an opportunity for people to be taken advantage of, both on the nanny and family sides. Therefore, there is<span style="color:#0000CD"> no set amount or award wage specifically allocated to nannies </span>and or nanny share arrangements.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="color:#FF0000">A sole care nanny</span></strong>, whereby they work for one family, can cost anywhere between $20-40p/hr, with <strong><span style="color:#FF0000">$25-27</span></strong> being the average. As a general rule of thumb, the nanny that takes on two families in a <strong><span style="color:#FF0000">nanny share</span></strong> arrangement would charge <span style="color:#FF0000"><strong>approximately 30% more</strong></span> per hour.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Below is a table to illustrate approximate hourly rates based on this theory. </strong></span><span style="font-size:14px">This estimated guide is based on two families each having one child. If a family has another child, a suggested rate is to add <strong>another $3 per/child onto the hourly rate.</strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#0000CD">sole charge hourly rate &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;nanny share rate per hour &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; rate per/family per hour</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp; $22.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $30.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $15.00</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp; $25.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $33.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $16.50 </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp; $27.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $35.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;$17.50</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp; $30.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $40.00 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $20.00</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Whether you employ a nanny at the lower or higher end of this guide will be based upon the following factors:</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">First and foremost, as with most areas of employment, the<span style="color:#FF0000"> more experience</span> the employee has, <span style="color:#FF0000">the higher they charge </span>for their services. Its no different in the nanny industry. A nanny who has over 10years experience will be a lot more expensive than the 19 year old straight out of high school. Thats one of the beautiful aspects of nanny sharing. You can afford that fully qualified nanny with 10years experience at a cost less than an inexperienced junior. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000">Location. </span>Nannies can be more expensive in more affluent suburbs </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000">How many hours</span> is the nanny required? Full-time nannies sometimes offer a slightly lower hourly rate. Is the nanny qualified? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000">Qualification levels </span>range from the most basic cert 3 in child care through to Mothercraft nurses and Degrees in Early childhood education. Qualified nannies generally charge a higher rate dependant on their level of education. There is a lot of hype in the media at present regarding the Government recognising nannies as registered carers so families can claim the same rebates as they do for centre based care. When this is passed through, it will be required that all nannies have a minimum of cert 3 in order for the families to claim.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Has the nanny had <span style="color:#FF0000">experience with multiples?</span> twins/triplets. A particularly relevant factor effecting nanny share arrangements, as there is usually 2 or more children around similar age requiring care.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Is the nanny<span style="color:#FF0000"> first aid trained? </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Does the nanny speak good english. Is he/she a<span style="color:#FF0000"> permanent resident</span> working as a career nanny or a travelling student looking for extra cash?</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong>OTHER FINANCIAL OBLIGATIONS TO CONSIDER WHEN DECIDING ON A NANNY SHARE ARRANGEMENT INCLUDE</strong>:</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#0000CD">Will all the costs be split 50/50 </span>between the families? For example, should I pack food/nappies for my baby or will the other family supply depending on where the care takes place. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Do I or the other family have a car the nanny can drive or do we need to pay a<span style="color:#0000CD"> car allowance?</span> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Does my nanny have an ABN so she can sort out her own tax or do I need to set up a PAYG. If the nanny does not have an ABN, will one family become the main employer to reduce the<span style="color:#0000CD"> tax</span>, or will both families pay separately meaning the nanny with have two employers?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">If the nanny is employed for 30 or more hours it is mandatory that they be paid <span style="color:#0000CD">superannuation.</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#0000CD">Sick pay and holiday pay</span> is payable pro-rata with the hours worked, just like any other employee. In the event that your child is sick, the nanny will care for your child provided the sickness isn&#39;t highly contagious. Both families are still expected to pay the nanny for the day even if one family decides to stay home with their sick child.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#0000CD">&nbsp;What supplies</span> will I need to purchase so my child can be cared for appropriately in the other families home? Porta-cot? High chair? Car seat? Double stroller? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What<span style="color:#0000CD"> insurances </span>do i need? Car insurance if the nanny will use your car. Public liability to cover accidents within the home. Your nanny should have her own nanny insurance.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">To find a suitable family match in your local area to engage in a nanny share arrangement, jump onto the website and create your profile now!</span></p>\n\n<p><a href="http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au">http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au</a></p>\n', 'how-much-should-i-expect-to-pay-a-shared-nanny', '2014-11-30'),
(6, 'What happens when someone is unwell in a nanny share arrangement?', '4e04352c1dabe4abd7f3f25c06570856.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#0000CD">At some time</span> through the duration of your nanny share arrangement, <span style="color:#800080">someone will be unwell. </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">It may be the children, the nanny or one of the parents. It&#39;s important to <span style="color:#FF0000">address this possibility from the beginning</span> to ensure everyone has a clear understanding of how to deal with the situation when it occurs. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#0000CD">Agreements may vary</span> between families and nannies, but always remember to <span style="color:#0000CD">empathise in times of illness, respect any agreements</span> that have been made and remember that a little flexibility can go a long way. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="font-size:16px">Based on the following nanny share arrangement there are a few options for dealing with sick days.</span></strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#800080">Family A has a 10 month old son.</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#A52A2A">Family B has a 1yr old daughter. </span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">They have hired a shared nanny as a <span style="color:#006400">permanent part-time employee </span>and the care takes place in both homes on a rotating weekly roster. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#006400">Scenario 1: The nanny is unwell.</span> Do I<span style="color:#A52A2A"> still need to pay the nanny </span>if she is unwell and unable to care of the children?<strong><span style="color:#A52A2A"> YES</span></strong>. Your nanny is hired by you as an employee and therefore is entitled to the same sick leave benefits as child care workers under the state award. The NSW standard sick leave entitlement is 8 days in the first year or pro-rata for the hours worked based on a full-time contract. Be clear to have a procedure in place regarding when the nanny needs to notify you of sickness, e.g. the night before when possible.&nbsp;Most nannies are aware of the inconvenience which can be caused if they are unable to care for your children on the required days. A good nanny will attempt to use minimal sick entitlement days, and return to work even when she is not 100%, on the grounds that they have a quiet day at home with the children and implement extra hygiene precautions to prevent spreading any germs. If your nanny is hired on a casual basis, they may agree to waive sick leave yet request a higher hourly rate of pay. <span style="color:#2F4F4F"><strong>Speaking from experience, the chance of you having to cover sick days for your nanny will be far less than having to stay home from work to care for a sick baby if they attend day care.</strong></span> Many nannies are part of a nanny network and may be able to offer referrals for a replacement nanny if they are unwell.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Ideally, one parent from each family can agree to share the cover for sick days. For example, the first time the nanny calls in sick, Mother A stays home from work and cares for the children from both families. On the second occasion the nanny is sick, if it shall happen, Mother B will sacrifice a day at the office and take on care of the the children. This way, if the nanny is sick 4 times in a year, both families will only loose 2 days at work. Try to<span style="color:#FF0000"> be flexible </span>around this. For&nbsp;example, if its family B&#39;s turn to cover the sick day but the mother has an important day packed with back-to-back meetings, perhaps Mother B could offer to cover that day provided Mother A can cover the next 2. Make sure both families are comfortable with any such agreement from the beginning. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#800080">SCENARIO 2: Family A&#39;s son is unwell.</span> Your nanny will still care for you child if he is sick. The decision around this one is <span style="color:#800080">reflective of </span>what <span style="color:#800080">particular illness</span> he has. If its a contagious virus then Family B needs to be notified to decide if they&#39;d prefer to keep their daughter away. The nanny should also be notified if either children have a contagious illness. Most nannies will still care for your children if they are sick, and its always a good question to ask the nanny in the interview if they have had all the typical childhood diseases and if they are immunised. If son A has a cold and is a little snotty, the nanny will be able to monitor their movements closely to assist in preventing cross-contamination. Whatever decision is reached by the families, the nanny is entitled to the full rate of pay for the day. If the nanny chooses to not care for either family for any reason other than he or she being sick themselves, than he or she is not entitled to payment. If either family decides they are not comfortable with care of both children to take place, they are still required to pay their share for the day. Again, exercise some empathy and understanding and remain flexible to keep everyone happy. If the nanny works for family B on Mon,Tues,Weds and Family A on Mondays and Tuesday only, perhaps a swap day to Wednesday could be arranged. Nanny sharing is like a team sport where all the players need to work together to win. SCENARIO 3: The father from family B is unwell and home in bed and its their turn to host care at their house. Nobody wants to stay home in bed from work recovering from sickness with a houseful of children! Be flexible to offer your home for care on these days and if possible give notice to the other family the night before. WHEN DOING REFERENCE CHECKS FOR PROSPECTIVE NANNIES, BE SURE TO ASK PREVIOUS EMPLOYERS HOW OFTEN THE NANNY WAS AWAY DUE TO SICKNESS. This should give a fairly good indication as to whether or not it will be a regular problem in your nanny share arrangement. If your baby is in long day care you will pay for any day they are sick and unable to attend. The centre will most likely call you to collect your child if they believe he or she is too unwell to be in attendance. Most babies are sick more in their first year than any other time during their lives as their tiny bodies try to build immunities to nasty germs. The exposure to germs is far less with a nanny than in a day care setting. Babies can be exposed to germs of up to 72 different children each day depending on the size of the child care centre. In a nanny share arrangement, their tiny bodies only need to cope with germs from the nanny and the other family so the chance of them becoming ill is drastically reduced. HAPPY NANNY SHARING!</span></p>\n', 'what-happens-when-someone-is-unwell-in-a-nanny-share-arrangement', '2014-11-30');
