(8, 'The many types of child care explained...', 'e61f5534a0fb57f84099dd7e14c18649.JPG', 'The road to choosing the right type of child care......\n\nThere is a wide range of child care options available in Australia. The first step in deciding which option is best for your family, is understanding exactly what each service provides.\n\n\nLONG DAY CARE: Centre based care operating for a minimum of 8 hours per day, with most opening from 730am-6pm, 50 weeks per year.  Most centres provide meals and a developmental program for the children. Centres must pass Government accreditation standards to be able to offer fee subsidies. Staffing must adhere to DOCS requirements in both numbers and qualification levels. Centres are either community based non-profit,  work/study based, or privately owned. Unfortunately, even with Government standards in place, there is a wide range in quality of services across Australia.  LDC can be an affordable option for families, however, there is no flexibility with lateness, which can incur very expensive late fees. The ratio for adult/child care in NSW is 1:4(children aged 0-24mnths), 1:5(children aged 24-36mnths), 1:11 (children aged 36mnths+).  In the event that your child has a contagious illness, they will be restricted from attending the centre until all symptoms have cleared. Payment is still required if your child does not attend on his or her usual days. Popular centres have long waiting lists and often require a non-refundable deposit to secure a place on their wait list. As an ex-teacher in a privately run 72place LDC, I personally felt that the children under 2 were not receiving the close attention they need due to staff restrictions. Centres often run based on their routines and not on specific individual needs of each and every child in attendance. Be sure to investigate centres thoroughly before accepting placement.\n\nPRESCHOOL:  Centre based care usually operating from 9am-3pm, catering for children aged 3yrs+ and often with the requirement that your child is toilet-trained. They should have a preschool readiness program in place to prepare your child for school.  As with LDC, some preschools are privately owned and others are community based. Most preschools run a 2 or 3 day programme based on the childs age and offer little flexibility around choice of days.  Preschools generally operate to school terms. Food is rarely provided in Preschools and families are required to send their childs food for the day, respecting any food restrictions in place with the centres policies.  Preschools have similar standards to abide by as LDC and also offer subsidised fees based on family income. Preschool care is highly recommended to assist with your childs social skills but has very limited hours for dual working families. \n\n\nFAMILY DAY CARE: Home based care which operates in the carers home. Family Day Care operates under the same National Quality Framework as LDC. Family day carers must possess at minimum, a Cert 111 in children''s services and a current first aid certificate.  FDC co-ordinators monitor the services with regular visits, ensuring the environment meets safety standards. The FDC can assist in finding alternative care in the event that your carer is unwell. The carer can care for up to 5 children under school age, and can also provide before and after school care for children up to the age of 12years. This type of care is recommended if you want siblings cared for together in a home based environment. Deregulation of FDC means theres a huge variation in fees.  Some carers provide food and supplies such as nappies/linen, but many require that you provide these yourself. This type of care can provide flexibility with hours, but is dependant on the actual service you choose. Having worked as a FDC co-ordinator, I  have personally witnessed a range of service from poor through to excellent, so I recommend meticulous research into the particular service you choose. FDC allows families to claim the child care benefit (CCB) based on their income. \n\nSOLE CHARGE NANNY: A nanny is hired by a family as an employee and comes to your home to care for your children whilst you are at work.  This can be on a casual, part-time or full-time basis as agreed upon in the family/nanny contract. This form of child care can be expensive, depending on the experience and qualification levels of your chosen nanny. Children cared for by a nanny are not restricted to a centre environment but rather, enjoy the familiarity of their own home joined with exciting outings in their immediate surroundings.  At present, the government has not recognised nannies as being an approved form a child care so families cannot claim the child care benefit. However,  families can claim the child care rebate (CCR) provided that the nanny is registered with the Family Assistance Office, which is not means tested. A sole charge nanny is responsible for the care of all the children living in your home. Some nannies will provide extra services such as cooking the family meal, folding the washing and running household errands. In the event that your child is unwell, the nanny will still come to your home and provide them with attentive care. Live-in nannies fall under the category of Au pairs. Nannies follow the childs routine as requested by the family, Qualified career nannies can provide excellent advise for families regarding their children.\n\nSHARED NANNY:  A cheaper alternative to sole charge nanny, with comparable benefits. One nanny is hired by 2 families and cares for all of their children together at the same time, either in one of the nominated family homes, or alternating between the 2 homes each week. All costs are split between the 2 families. On average, a shared nanny will charge approximately 30% extra per hour, which is then divided between the two families. For example, a sole charge nanny costing $25p/hour will charge, $32.50p/hour, resulting in each family paying $16.25p/hr for the same level of care. Nanny sharing is a growing trend in Australia as it allows families to enjoy the luxury of having a nanny care for their children at home, without the high price of a sole charge nanny. Ideally, 2 families have similar aged children that follow a similar routine, share similar interests and and live locally to each other. Its suggested that a maximum of 4 children be cared for at once. In the event that 3 families wish to share the nanny, the hourly rate will be slightly higher again, but divided 3 ways to reduce costs even further. For example, the $25p/hr sole charge nanny, cares for 3 babbies from 3 different families, costing the families around $13 each per hour. Nanny sharing can be a very socially satisfying experience and is a win-win for everyone involved provided everything is agreed upon at commencement of care. In some instances, sharing a nanny can be a cheaper alternative to placing your baby in centre based care.  NannyShareAustralia is an online site which matches like-minded families looking for a nanny share arrangement, and will be launched in November 2014!!!\n\nMUMMY NANNY: An experienced nanny, who now has a child of her own, comes to care for your children in your home and brings their own child with them. On average, mummy nannies charge approximately 20% less than their usual rate as a sole charge nanny. With this arrangement, families and the nanny must be clear  about the procedure in place in the event that either your child, or their child is unwell. This can be a very successful arrangement provided the nanny and family have parallel beliefs and ideas in regards to raising their children. \n\nMOTHERS HELPER: Mothers helpers are exactly as it sounds. Usually the mother isn''t working and simply needs an extra pair of hands. Mothers helpers rates are on par with sole charge nannies, but again is dependant on a range of factors. e.g., duties required, hours worked, full-time or part time basis...etc  If your child is clingy or experiencing separation anxiety, a mothers helper may end up more of a hindrance than a help. \n\nAu pair: An au pair is a live-in nanny. Their hourly rate is inexpensive, however boarding and food is provided by you. They usually provide between 20-40hours of care each week.  Most Au Pairs are travelling students with english as their second language. They are often young and inexperienced, and working in Australia on temporary visas.  Ideally, your home will have a separate living area for the AuPair. This form of child care can be effective providing both the Aupair and the host family are clears about all aspects of caring for the children and the living arrangements. Communication breakdowns can easily occur if there is a huge language barrier. AuPairs do not tend to commit to long term agreements. \n\n\nBABYSITTER: A babysitter provides supervision of your children for short periods of time, mostly on a casual basis. Babysitters range from high school students through to fully qualified and experienced career nannies, which is reflective of their hourly rate. Babysitters are mostly called upon in the evenings when children are sleeping, hence why younger inexperienced carers can be used.\n\n\nProbably the largest factor influencing your choice of child care is costs. A sole charge nanny may be out of reach for many families,  but centre based care may come with inconvenience and hidden costs. Be careful to investigate all your options before deciding which form of care will best meet your family requirements.\n \nConsistency for your children is an important aspect to consider.\n', 'the-many-types-of-child-care-explained', '2014-11-30'),
(9, 'What is a mummy nanny?', '2a8115fd517267dcbd355f55ceef6a5b.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>A mummy-nanny is exactly what it sounds like. Its a nanny, who is also a mummy. </strong></span><span style="font-size:14px">Not to be confused with the term &#39;mothers helper&#39;. A mothers helper is often a young nanny seeking valuable experience working alongside a mother assisting in the care of her children. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">A mummy-nanny comes to your home to care for your child/children, bringing her own child with her. You go off to work, and the mummy-nanny cares for your children together with her own child in your home<strong><span style="color:#0000CD">. </span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="color:#0000CD">Why choose a mummy nanny? &nbsp;</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="color:#B22222">1. Cost effective.</span></strong> The mummy-nanny usually charges <strong>20% less per hour than a sole charge</strong> nanny. For example, the $25p/hr nanny will only cost $20 per hour. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="color:#B22222">2. Experience</span></strong>.The vast majority of mummy-nannys have years of experience as a nanny before choosing to become a mother themselves. They can be more understanding about child related issues that first time mothers face, having personally experienced themselves. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>3. Special bonds</strong></span>.Your child will have a constant playmate. This type of arrangement is especially beneficial to single child families. These relationships often become lifelong friendships. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>4. Care at home.</strong></span>Unlike nanny share arrangements where care may alternate each week between the homes of families involved, mummy nanny care will ALWAYS take place in your own home. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">If you are keen on the idea of a mummy nanny, its ideal to find a mummy nanny who has a child whom is of close age to your own and/or follows a similar routine. In some instances, the mummy nanny will have more than one child. Or you may have more than one child. A maximum of four children in care at the same time is suggested. A mummy nanny does not care for the child at her own home. This is classified as Family Day Care or Home Based Care. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">So you&#39;ve decided that a mummy nanny can work for you?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:18px"><strong><span style="color:#B22222">What questions should you ask in the interview process?</span></strong></span><span style="font-size:14px"> How old is your child? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you planning any more children in the near future? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you looking for a long term commitment? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you prepared to attend scheduled weekly activities? e.g. Gymbaroo, swimming lesson, etc</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Does your child have any food allergies?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What are your views towards healthy eating?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Does your child have any special needs considerations? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Do you have a clear driving record and car seats installed in your car?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What is your child&#39;s daily routine and are you flexible around it?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you comfortable with pets? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you comfortable with a swimming pool in the backyard and will you take the children swimming? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What days and hours of care can you commit to?Are you flexible with this?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What is your hourly rate? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you comfortable with taking the children on outings in the car?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are you ok with caring for my child when he/she is unwell? Do you have any planned holidays coming up? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What are your views and techniques towards discipline?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Do you allow your children to watch television and if yes, when, what and how long?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What are your expectations towards duties required as a nanny? eg. cooking/washing/cleaning? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Why did you choose to become a nanny? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What have you found to be the most challenging aspect about becoming a mum? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">What have you found to be the most rewarding aspect about being a mum? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">A mummy nanny arrangement can be an emotionally rewarding experience. Your child will be cared for by a professional, experienced nanny at a reduced rate.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">The <strong>two main reasons why families may choose to NOT engage in this type of arrangement</strong> are: </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">1. fear that the mummy nanny will focus all her attention on her own child, hence neglecting yours </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">2. fear that the mummy nanny will require extra leave in the event that her own child is unwell, or will not expose her own child to any illness that your child may have. <strong>To avoid either of these fears becoming a reality, be sure to select your mummy nanny carefully and address any concerns in the interview process. </strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>To find your perfect mummy nanny, or register as a mummy nanny, create your free profile now at: </strong></span><strong><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 205)"><a href="http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au">http://www.nannyshareaustralia.com.au</a></span></strong><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <u><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;</em></u></p>\n', 'what-is-a-mummy-nanny', '2014-12-02'),
(11, 'The 5 most important elements for a successful nanny share', 'a9ee2ca0067ce8d8aa403a8a6beaeb66.jpeg', ' The 5 most important elements for a successful nanny share                       \n\n\n\nHONESTY      CONSISTENCY          RESPECT            COMMUNICATION            EMPATHY        \n\n\nHonesty: The most important element required to maintain any healthy relationship. Without honesty, comes a luck of trust. And trust, is the fundamental basis for a happy nanny share arrangement. A strong sense of trust must be formed between both families and the nanny. Families must be completely honest about their requirements and values. Even the smallest white lie can damage trust. Nannies must be open and honest about anything and everything in regards to the children in their care. Any issues should be discussed immediately from all parties to prevent unwanted escalations.\n\nConsistency: Its vital that consistency flows from the families, through the nanny and onto the children. Children raised with consistent guidelines  and limits grow into happy, well adjusted little people. Lack of consistency creates confusion and frustration so its important that everyone involved in the nanny share arrangement implements similar structures and values. For example, if the parents says no to something, the nanny needs to follow through with the same. Consistency with disciplinary methods is paramount.\n\nRespect: This is a 2-way street. In order to gain respect, one must also give it. A nanny is not just an employee, she(or he, if its a manny) is the person that you are trusting to care for your most precious possessions. And from a nanny''s perspective, the parents aren''t  just a boss. They become friends, and sometimes even like family. Everyone must respect each others values and beliefs, which should be thoroughly discussed in the interview process. Role modelling respect in the company of the children is a priceless life lesson for them to witness and learn.\n\nCommunication:It can''t be stressed enough how crucial it is that both families clearly communicate their needs with each other and their prospective nanny. Unfortunately it''s not uncommon for nannies or families to feel disgruntled when certain duties are not completed or certain ideas are overlooked or changed. This is easily avoided by  concise clarity about the expectations required of everyone involved. A contract which outlines duties,hours, wages and conditions, can easily avoid any such issues. A daily diary is a very simple yet effective method of communicating in addition to daily discussions.\n\nEmpathy: A simple but powerful emotion that can make or break any relationship. No two people are the same, and too often we expect others to think and act the same way as we do. However, thats not the case. Remember that your nanny has a life outside of work and respect that but sticking to the agreed hours and job description outlined in the contract. Always discuss flexibility with your prospective nanny around working extra hours. And nannies should remember that the parents are often juggling corporate stress and shouldn''t be judged on their choices. A qualified nanny can offer professional advice and tips relating to child development, but must exercise empathy to understand why families make certain choices about raising their children. A little empathy goes a long way.\n\n\nIMPLEMENT AND REMEMBER THESE FIVE SIMPLE PRINCIPLES AND YOUR NANNY-SHARE ARRANGEMENT IS GUARANTEED TO BE A HUGE SUCCESS!\n\n\nHAPPY FAMILIES\nHAPPY NANNY \nHAPPY CHILDREN', 'the-5-most-important-elements-for-a-successful-nanny-share', '2014-12-16'),
(12, 'How to choose the right family for a nanny share arrangement', '1b3b44b4d25bcc4640c3c94914919e36.jpg', 'How to find the perfect family match for a successful nanny share arrangement\n\nFinding the right family to share a nanny is the first step in a rewarding nanny share agreement. There  are several methods of locating like-minded families. You can advertise your search for a family on social media in the hope there is a family located close to you that is looking to share a nanny on the same days as you require. You can contact one of the many nanny share agencies Australia wide, whom will do the searching for you, however placement fees can be costly. Or, as of November 2014, you can login to nannyshareaustralia.com.au, create your family profile and search the database for families within your area whom may be suitable. Once you have found a family who you believe may be a good fit, its paramount that the interview is comprehensive in covering anything and everything which may effect a nanny share arrangement.  Organise an informal meeting of families, preferably  with the entire family on each side in attendance. If the care is to occur alternatively each week in both  homes, arrange a meeting in each to ensure you are happy with the safety of the other families home setup.    \n\nBelow is a list of questions that can be discussed to decide whether the match is suitable.\n\n\nHow old is your child?  Are you planning any more children in the near future?\nAre you looking for a long term commitment with the nanny share arrangement?\nAre you willing to share with a third family, hence splitting the cost three ways?\nDoes your child attend any scheduled weekly activities? e.g. Gymbaroo, swimming lesson, etc\nDoes your child have any food allergies? What are your views towards healthy eating?\nDoes your child have any special needs considerations?\nAre you prepared to supply a portacot and car seat for your child?\nWhat is your child''s daily routine and are you flexible around it?\nAre you comfortable with pets?\nAre you comfortable with a swimming pool in the backyard and happy for the nanny to take your child swimming there in the warmer months?\nDo you already have a nanny or shall we find one together?\nWhat type of nanny are you looking for? mature aged? Experience level?\nWould you prefer a nanny with her own ABN or are you happy to set up a PAYG system? In the event the nanny does not have an ABN, will you take care of tax and super obligations or will we split it down the middle?\nWhat days and hours of care do you require. Are you flexible with this? When do you need care to commence?\nDo you want the care to take place in my home, your home, or alternate each week?\nWould you prefer to pack your childs food each week or are you happy to supply it depending on which home the care occurs in?\nAre you planning on moving or renovating in the  near future?\nHow much are you prepared to pay the nanny? \nAre you comfortable with a nanny taking your child on outings in the car?\nDo you have a car the nanny can use or shall we agree on a split car allowance?\nDo you have any religious beliefs which may impact on the arrangement?\nAre you ok with my child still receiving care at your home when he/she is unwell?\nDo you have any planned holidays coming up?\nWhat are your views and techniques towards discipline?\nDo you allow your children to watch television and if yes, when, what and how long?\nWhat are your expectations towards duties required of the nanny? eg. cooking/washing/cleaning?\nWhat is the most important goal for you in having your child cared for by a nanny?\nIn the event that our nanny is unwell, are you in a position to find alternate care, or would you be interested in sharing the sick days between us. i.e. we take on the responsibility of care on a shared basis. \n\nThe more questions you ask in the interview process, the better understanding you will have of the other families needs, values and ideas. Try to remain  flexible and compromise a little if needed, whilst maintaining honesty and without compromising your own needs and limitations.   You don''t need to have identical views on everything but its important that you agree on the main logistics and beliefs.  Don''t be disheartened if it takes several interviews to find the perfect family match. Its best to feel 100% certain from the beginning to minimise future disruption and inconsistencies for everyone involved. Always go with your gut, if something doesn''t feel right, than more than likely it will create problems down the track. \n\nSo, you''ve found your family match....now its time to secure the best nanny for the role. The nest blog will explain the process in achieving this goal, with a suggested list of questions to ask in the nanny interview.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 'how-to-choose-the-right-family-for-a-nanny-share-arrangement', '2014-12-18'),
(13, 'The best parenting books ', 'bc7fd0951b6107211554d7f470191a80.jpg', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>&#39;The New Basics&#39; by Michel Cohen is like my bible</strong>.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Over the past 15 years working as a nanny, Ive read and collected a library of books to further my knowledge around all child-related issues. Every book comes with its <strong>own sets of ideas</strong>, usually based on the values, experiences and research collated by the author. The New Basics is an easy go-to collection of alphabetically arranged addressing childhood issues ranging from discipline and diarrhoea through to nipple confusion and nosebleeds. The reason I love this book its due to its tried and tested success through my experience. My own personal values are on par with the no-nonsense methods of Michel Cohen, and through implementing many of his ideas Ive assisted families in raising their children to become healthy, happy and well-adjusted individuals. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Due to the Cyber-world in which we live today, we are inundated with information at the press of a finger. Same may say that books are becoming obsolete. However, I personally believe its important to obtain a small library of preferred books that we can access at any time. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Sometimes we need information, other times its inspiration or reassurance that we require. The world wide web has an overload of information, but finding an author whom you trust and respect is priceless.<strong> All children and their families are unique</strong>. Ideas and advice recommended in one book may work brilliantly for one family, but fail epically for the next. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>I feel that its important to: </strong></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>*read as many books as you can</strong>. The more information you have, the more power and understanding you can gain to make the most educated and suitable decisions.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">*realise that you <strong>may not agree with EVERYTHING written</strong> in a book and implementing some of its ideas will be a case of trial and error. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">*<strong>understand your own feelings</strong> towards child-related issues before purchasing a book. For example, if you prefer controlled crying as a sleep training method, ensure your book of choice follows similar principles. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">*ideally, <strong>keep an open-mind</strong> before ruling out any methods before you completely understand them. There are no right and wrongs of parenting. <strong>Never feel that you have failed</strong> if your child doesn&#39;t live up to the text book stereotypes. They are all individuals with different needs, wants, strengths and weaknesses. Always do what works best for the entire family. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">I have a compiled a list of what I consider to be the best books for parents and caregivers to address child-related topics to ensure a happy first 5 years. I have used much of the information from many of the listed books and am yet to read a few.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#ff0099"><strong>The list was also compiled based on recommendations from mothers and nannies of Sydney. </strong></span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="font-size:20px"><span style="color:#0000CD">Sleep Training Books </span></span></strong></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Sleeping like a baby (Pinky McKay) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Save our sleep for babies (Tizzie Hall) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The gift of sleep (Elizabeth Sloane) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Dream baby guide (Sheyne Rowleys) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">No Cry sleep solution (Elizabeth Pantley) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The complete sleep guide (Gina Ford)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Helping your baby to sleep (Beth MacGregor) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:20px"><strong>Books about discipline</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Discipline that works: 5 simple steps (Joyce Divinyi)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">1.2.3 magic effective discipline for children 2-12 (Thomas w Feline) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">How to talk to kids so they will listen and listen so kids will talk (Adele Faber) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Raising your spirited child (Mary Sherry) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Siblings without rivalry (Adele Faber)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:20px"><strong>Books about child development and suggested techniques</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:16px"> </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Nurture shock: new thinking about children (Po Bronson) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The happiest toddler on the block (Harvey Karl)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Einstein never used flashcards: How our children really learn and why they need to play more and memorise less (Roberta Golinkoff)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Playful learning: Develop your childs sense of joy and wonder (Maria Bruehl)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Whats going on in there?how the brain and mind develop in the first 5 years (Lise Eliot) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The whole brain child (Danial J Siegel) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Toddler Taming (Christopher Green)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The mighty toddler (Robyn Barker) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:20px"><strong>Baby books</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:16px"> </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">What to expect when you&#39;re expecting (Heidi Murkoff)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">What to expect in the first year (Heidi Murkoff) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The baby book (William Sears) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">ABC and 123 for beginners (Beverly Malcom) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Dr Spocks baby and child care Baby Love (Robyn Barker) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Travels with baby (Shelly Rivolli) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:20px"><strong>Cookbooks</strong></span></span><span style="font-size:16px"> </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Weelicious (Catherine McCord) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Starting Solids (Annabel Karmel) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The fussy eater (Annabel Karmel) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Top 100 baby purees (Annabel Karmel)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The healthy baby meal planner (Annabel Karmel)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Breast, bottle, bowl: the best baby fed baby book (Anne Hills)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">The baby-led weaning cookbook (Gill Rapley) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Sage spoonfuls (liza huber) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Parents need to eat too (Debbie Koenig) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Food babies love (Emily fupuche) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px">Cut out the crap (Collate white) </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color:#ff0099"><strong><span style="font-size:16px">HAPPY READING!!!!</span></strong></span></p>\n', 'the-best-parenting-books', '2015-01-12'),
(14, 'Do I need an employment CONTRACT?', '300ce38036d39955071e0f6c2d8fe63f.jpg', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>Am I legally required to provide my nanny with an employment contract?</strong></span><strong> <span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px">NO</span></span></strong></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>Should I provide my nanny with an employment</strong> <strong>contract? <span style="color:#ff0099">ABSOLUTELY YES!</span></strong></span><strong> </strong></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px"><strong>Having a contract in place is a win-win for the families and nannies involved. </strong></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Some families hire a nanny based purely on verbal terms of agreement. This is mostly a recipe for future problems. Having worked as a nanny for 2 decades, I have found myself in both contractual and non-contractual nanny agreements. The long term positions all had a contract in place. The short-term positions DID NOT have a contract in place. Oh, and when I say short term...that wasn&#39;t what they set out to be. All my positions were entered into with hope and expectation that they would be long term, because lets face it, no-one wants to be up heaved in their jobs every few months. But the non-contractual positions were short term, exactly because of that. Without a contract, there were unclear expectations from both sides as to my duties as a nanny and all monetary obligations involved. When issues arose, they were mostly a result of a misunderstanding and lack of clarity from the onset. Without a contract in place, there was nothing to fall back on. Ive met hundreds of nannies over the years, each with their own set of work issues that they&#39;ve had to deal with throughout their own work life as career nannies. Each and every problem that Ive heard, was the result of mis-communication and an absence of contractual clarity. To offer advise to such problems, Id often find myself asking &quot;what does it say in your contract?&quot;. If I had a dollar for every time the answer was &quot;I don&#39;t have a contract&quot;...Id be rich! </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">When you join the gym, you sign a contract. When you secure a mobile phone plan, you sign a contract. When you get married, you sign a contract. When you buy a house, you sign a contract. When you hire someone to care for your beloved children...or when you agree to care for someone else&#39;s beloved children.....<span style="color:#ff0099">YOU SHOULD HAVE A CONTRACT IN PLACE!</span> </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">An employment contract is beneficial both to the nanny and the family involved in the agreement. Hiring a nanny is a probably the most <strong>important business agreement </strong>you will make as a mother, so its crucial to get it right from the start. The family becomes the employer...and the nanny becomes the employee......just like any other work agreement situation Some families may fear that a contract with tarnish the relationship that are are building with their nanny. In actual fact, it assists in creating the perfect understanding required from everyone involved in the relationship by outlining clear and concise ground rules. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Sample contracts can be found online or you may wish to draw one up yourself as a family. Some nannies may offer a contract that they&#39;ve used in the past, or you can sit down together with the nanny and decide what needs to be included. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Nothing is too small to include in your contract if you believe it will have an impact on the success of the relationship. Some basic information that should be addressed in a contract includes:</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Work days and hours </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Wages and pay schedule </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Tax obligations super/annual leave/sick entitlements and overtime allowances</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Car usage/allowance </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Termination </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Detailed job duties and expectations </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">Additional costs (petty cash)</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">A contract should be offered as a <strong>negotiable document </strong>and signed by all parties only once full agreement is made regarding EVERY aspect of the given contract. </span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:14px">When entering into a <span style="color:#ff0099">nanny share</span> arrangement, the contract needs to cover the nanny involved, as well as all the families agreeing into the contract. The nanny share contract is therefore a little more involved as there is a minimum of 3 parties involved. A sample nanny share contract can be downloaded from our Q&amp;As section.&nbsp;</span></p>\n', 'do-i-need-an-employment-contract', '2015-01-16'),
(15, 'Does your child play with coins???', 'c212341c85a3ab2eff30e2948000cab8.jpeg', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:18px">One of my pet hates as a nanny over the years, is the high prevalence of toddlers playing with coins.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">I&#39;ve encountered it in every single job. Strangely, small children seem fascinated with money. They will pick it up in their travels. They will collect coins. They&#39;ll carry them around. They&#39;ll ask adults if they have any to add to their stash. They can entertain </span>themselves for endless hours with these little round metal objects.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#ff0099">But where have these coins been? </span>That is the thought that always comes to my mind. In the deep pockets of a junkie perhaps..or dropped underneath a shoe that has remnants of dog feces? It mortifies me to begin to even<span style="color:#0000CD"> imagine the bacteria </span>that is present on these small round objects that toddlers insist on playing with! They play with the coins, before you know it, their fingers are in their mouth.......eeeewh, this<span style="color:#0000CD"> must be making our kids sick right?</span> So I thought Id share my dislike in my blog, hoping to justify my years of distaste in this common &#39;toy&#39; of choice.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">I researched the topic, hoping to share the information about this germ spreading activity, but instead was modestly surprised with what I learnt! </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#FF0000"><span style="font-size:14px"><strong>Australian coins are made from:</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<h2 style="color:Blue;font-weight:bold;"><span style="font-size:14px"><strong><span style="color:#000000">silver- 75% copper and 25% nickel gold </span></strong></span></h2>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong>$1- 92% copper, 6% aluminium and 2% nickel gold </strong></span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp;$2- 92% cupro nickel, 6% aluminium and 2% nickel (25% nickel).</span></strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px">Copper, or cupro nickel (which is 75% copper), contains anti-microbial properties that ward off any pernicious bacteria and viruses</span></span><span style="font-size:14px">. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">So these tiny objects that have caused me so much distress over the years <span style="color:#0000CD">aren&#39;t quite the disease-spreading culprits as I once believed.</span> Dr Frank Vriesekoop from Ballarat University, claims that the <span style="color:#ff0099">levels of bacteria found on Australian coins is so low, its impossible for them to cause cross infection related illness.</span> Phew...big sigh of relief! All my fears about currency hygiene, or lack there of, have been completely unwarranted. I&#39;m glad Ive written this post, not only to share the awareness with you, but its one less thing I have to worry about now for the toddlers in my care. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Of course, there is still the concern of the $2 coin being the<span style="color:#ff0099"> perfect size for a</span> <span style="color:#ff0099">choking disaster.</span>....but thankfully the the flavour of copper doesn&#39;t appeal! So anytime a toddler in my care in the future feels the desire to play with coins......it will be done so with close supervision and the knowledge at least, that they&#39;re are not contracting a virus whilst doing so!</span></p>\n', 'does-your-child-play-with-coins', '2015-01-17');
