(16, 'My toddler only eats chips!', '349cfef93f6ece66c9b4f2f8a11b3bb6.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:18px">&nbsp;<em>Instilling healthy food habits in children and avoiding the creation of a fussy eater............. </em></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">When I hear a parent, or caregiver, say &quot;my toddler will only eat chips&quot;, my first train of thought is...&quot;why is your toddler eating chips?&quot; I&#39;m not a junk food Nazi, and I believe in moderation, but to introduce something so deliciously desirable as hot chips and then wonder why toddlers want them. In&nbsp;many nanny positions I have held, parents have asked &quot;why will my child eat vegetables for you and not for me?&quot;</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">I&#39;m not a child psychologist nor an expert in nutrition, but I&#39;m a career nanny of almost 20years and have carried out hundreds of thousand of toddler meal times during this time. Every child is unique, but simple principles can be applied to them all with success. <span style="color:#FF0000">Persistence and consistency is of fundamental</span> importance. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">As with any aspect of raising healthy happy children, if you <span style="color:#FF0000">understand the &#39;why&#39;</span> behind the behaviour, then you&#39;re success in addressing it will be ten-fold! </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>Why will my toddler only eat chips?</strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Umm, perhaps because they taste so much better than broccoli? Is it because they are too tired at the moment to try anything new? </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Are they feeling unwell and just the thought of steamed fish is turning their stomach. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px">Or is it simply because, the option of having chips for dinner is a choice that you have allowed. So how do you stop your toddler from consuming a hot-chip laden diet and replace it with healthy well-balanced meals? <span style="color:#FF0000">Healthy eating habits should</span> <span style="color:#FF0000">be introduced as young as possible.</span> The 3 main meals should ideally include some protein, starch and fruit and vegetables.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#0000FF"><strong>1 DON&#39;T INTRODUCE CHIPS IN THE FIRST PLACE</strong></span><strong>!</strong></span> If you already have, that&#39;s ok, just don&#39;t offer them again. If you&#39;re heading out for dinner and there&#39;s a strong possibility that the beloved chip will be present, fill them up on some vegetables beforehand and they&#39;ll be too full to consume these little strips of potatoes soaked in oil and smothered in salt.</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>2. ROLE MODEL</strong></span></span> healthy eating habits. Don&#39;t sit down and delight your own senses with pork crackling and hot chips, and expect your toddler to devour a plate of stemmed veggies. Toddlers do not understand the nutritional benefits of healthy food or the detrimental effects of &quot;sometimes&#39; foods, so discussing it with them is pointless. Only YOU can control how often they are given such choices.</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>3. TIME YOUR MEALS EFFECTIVELY</strong></span></span>, Keep a diary for a week about what your child eats when. If they tend to eat more in the morning, jam-pack breakfast with loads of goodness and focus less on the evening meal. Children tend to eat less when they are tired. Who says you can&#39;t have chicken pasta for breakfast and Weetbix for dinner?! Don&#39;t rush meal times. If your child is a slow eater, allow ample time for them to finish their meal. Patience is paramount. Provide light healthy snacks during meals but do not encourage grazing.</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>4. UNDERSTAND WHAT YOUR CHILD MEANS.</strong></span></span> So your child says &quot;I don&#39;t like chicken risotto&quot;, even though they&#39;ve enjoyed it 300 times in the past! They may not have developed the language skills they need to express what they really mean. I &quot;don&#39;t like&quot; is often miss used by toddlers who want to say&quot;i don&#39;t feel like it&quot;. So don&#39;t give up on those recipes that they once loved, chances are, they will &quot;like it&quot; the next time they &quot;feel like it&quot;.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong><span style="color:#0000FF">5. KEEP OFFERING SMALL AMOUNTS </span></strong></span>of new and different foods&nbsp;on the side of their plate, even if they say they don&#39;t like it. It may mean throwing out half a tomato everyday for a month, but eventually they will enjoy a variety of foods as their taste buds develop and change. Encourage them to try, but NEVER force them to eat anything. Accept that there will be foods that you may need to give up on, but give it a month, and try again a couple of weeks later. I&#39;m 41, and I still don&#39;t like mushrooms!!!</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><strong><span style="font-size:16px">6. EXPOSE THEM TO A VARIETY OF FOODS.</span></strong></span> The proof is in the pudding here if you look at what children eat for breakfast around the world. I&#39;m sure I could count on one hand how many toddlers living in Japan eat Vegemite on toast to start the day, or Australian toddlers that choose sashimi as their breakfast of choice for that matter. Only in the past 10 years, Australian children are indulging in Sushi as their chosen take away.</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>7. DON&#39;T STRESS IF&nbsp;YOUR TODDLER EATS NOTHING AT A MEAL. </strong></span></span>Look at how much they&#39;ve eaten over the week. Their reason for not eating could include a lack of hunger, over tiredness, teething or sickness. We as adults know there are times when are appetites are low, unfortunately toddlers don&#39;t have the cognitive or language abilities to explain that. Trust me, eventually they will become hungry, and will welcome some steamed greens! Children can survive for a week without food, provided they are getting fluids. Its safe to say that the incidence of starvation in Australia is not an issue of concern. As soon as you see signs of a &#39;fussy eater&#39;.....letting them go a little hungry in the short term will benefit greatly in the long! Im not suggesting you starve your child, they WILL eat when they&#39;re hungry,</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong><span style="color:#ff0099">8. MAKE MEAL TIMES FUN.</span></strong></span> Sit down together as a family if you can. Limit distractions such as television. Its unnecessary to create games or tricks to encourage feeding, but it can be fun. Remember though, if you made a food face yesterday, your toddler may demand it again today and tomorrow, and the next day.......so be aware of possible consequences of your actions! If possible, involve toddlers in meal prep. Miss 2.5yrs usually consumes an entire serve of salad without even realising it when she is involved in cutting up some of the soft vegetables.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong><span style="color:#0000CD">9. DON&#39;T BRIBE CHILDREN WITH TREATS.</span></strong></span> Do you have dessert every night?!! Children are not born gluttons...but daily dessert offerings can develop this. Treats on special occasions such as parties are an unavoidable part of life, don&#39;t even try to fight that one. And if you really can&#39;t resist from the dessert bribe. At least, make it a healthy treat like yoghurt, and NEVER EVER allow it if they haven&#39;t taken a considerable bite&nbsp;out of their dinner.</p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#ff0099"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>10.PROVIDE CHOICE</strong></span></span>. Children are egocentric. Making decisions helps them feel independent. So always give options at meal time, ensuring the options are appropriate. For example, &quot;would you like tomatoes or cucumbers with your dinner?&quot; Never give open ended choices such as &quot;what would you like for dinner?&quot;....as your answer may well be &quot;CHIPS&quot;!!!!</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:14px"><strong>If you have followed all these basic fundamentals, yet meal times continue to be food-dodging episodes where peas are torpedoed across the floor and your childs lungs are reaching unimaginable decibels in stubborn refusal to eat.........this is how to handle it in four simple steps! </strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="color:#000000">1.Stay calm. </span></p>\n\n<p>2.Explain to the child that meal time is over and the next meal time will be in 3-4 hours.</p>\n\n<p>3.Wipe down the child, wipe down the highchair, collect the sea of peas off the floorboards.</p>\n\n<p>4.DO NOT give any food until the next meal time. Keep repeating this strategy....children learn through repetition. Give in once, you&#39;ve given in a thousand times.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Healthy eating is an important issue to address when entering a nanny share agreement. Beliefs around nutrition should be discussed with the shared family and nanny so there is consistency around meal times.</strong></p>\n', 'my-toddler-only-eats-chips', '2015-01-19'),
(18, 'Why puzzles are so important for your childs development ', 'b80027e05745ca0f6c10f7a8dff4567c.jpg', '<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#808080"><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>There&#39;s a lot to be said about the humble puzzle. A simple toy that teaches endless skills to our young.</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">There are wooden puzzles, plastic puzzles, magnetic puzzles, foam puzzles, floor puzzles, 3d puzzles, alphabet puzzles, dressing puzzles,number puzzles, themed puzzles and even language puzzles...the list goes on and on!</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Some of the important skills children learn through puzzle play include:</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000"><strong>FINE MOTOR SKILLS</strong></span> and hand eye-coordination increasing pinching and grasping skills which assist in future skills required for handwriting.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>COGNITIVE SKILLS</strong></span>:..matching shapes, matching colours, problem solving, especially targeting&nbsp; spatial awareness regarding sizing as well as location, prepositions like in/out/behind/over/under/inside/outside, promote memory, challenge thinking processes.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000"><strong>SOCIAL SKILLS</strong></span>: turn taking if puzzling with another child, or team work skills if puzzling with a group.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>EMOTIONAL SKILLS</strong></span>: developing a sense of achievement on completion of a puzzle. Promote independence.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px"><span style="color:#FF0000"><strong>LANGUAGE SKILLS:</strong></span> questioning skills &quot;where does this go, how can we make it fit&quot;,preposition and location expressive language that assists in spacial awareness e.g. in, out, behind, under, etc</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#800080"><em><strong><span style="font-size:14px">Puzzle can be a test of patience for many adults. Next time your toddler is struggling to connect two puzzles pieces, put on a rubber glove and try it yourself..it will help you you understand how they feel.</span></strong></em></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>To make puzzle time more enjoyable follow these steps:</strong></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Ensure the puzzle is age appropriate.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Choose themed puzzles that reflect your childs interest</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Start puzzles as young as possible...babies as young as 6months can begin with simple shape matching puzzles. If your baby can pick objects up with one and hand and is beginning to manipulate objects such as placing them into containers..its time to begin puzzle play!</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Start out with puzzles no more than 3 pieces in total</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Keep pieces together in boxes to avoid them becoming mixed up. Mark the back of the pieces to make it easier to pack away</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Eliminate other distractions such as tv</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Do not encourage puzzle time when your child is tired. Tiredness will decrease their problem solving skills, hence resulting in an inability to complete the puzzle and a a blow to their self-esteem.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">For larger piece puzzles, begin with areas of the puzzles that have colourful and easily recognisable pieces that can be more readily matched</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">Use the &#39;scaffolding&#39; method. This simply means providing your child with enough guidance and assistance to complete a puzzle without actually doing it for them. For younger children, almost place the piece in the correct position, next suggest the correct piece and have your child work out the correct angle, next only suggest the piece and have the child decide where it goes....</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#B22222"><span style="font-size:14px">PUZZLES APPROPRIATE FOR VARIOUS AGE GROUPS:</span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">6-12months</span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">1-3pieces,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp;Inset puzzles,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp;easy grasp knobs,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp;simple shapes,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">&nbsp;matching pictures on puzzle board under pieces,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">1-2 years</span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">3-15 pieces,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">peg puzzles</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">chunky pieces</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">2-4years</span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">introduce floor puzzles,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">10-35 pieces,</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="color:#0000CD"><span style="font-size:14px">4-6years</span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">20-60pieces</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><span style="font-size:14px">introduce 3D puzzles</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align:center"><strong><span style="color:#B22222"><span style="font-size:14px">Puzzle abilities will vary greatly amongst children. Like with most activities..practise makes perfect!</span></span></strong></p>\n', 'why-puzzles-are-so-important-for-your-childs-development', '2015-02-10'),
(19, 'How much should I pay my babysitter? ', 'bc9441764a556b89b2822b55be919503.jpg', '<p><span style="font-size:16px">This is a commonly asked question amongst mums when deciding on hiring a babysitter to care for their child/children.</span></p>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">The answers varies from&nbsp;anywhere as low as <span style="color:#B22222">$14 through to $30</span> per hour.</span></p>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">The price you pay will be&nbsp;determined by many factors, such as:</span></p>\n</div>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">The&nbsp;<strong><span style="color:#B22222">age</span>&nbsp;</strong>of the babysitter (junior or adult)</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>Experience</strong></span>&nbsp;level i.e. how many years experience the babysitter has had working with children and does it consist of nannying and/or centre based care or primarily babysitting jobs</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>Qualifications</strong></span>. A carer with an early childhood degree will have a background in child development which will assist with difficult child-related incidents which could occur. For example, handling a tantrum or knowledge surrounding child safety practises.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Socio-economic&nbsp;<strong><span style="color:#B22222">area and location</span>&nbsp;</strong>of where the babysitting will take place. A babysitter in the eastern suburbs may charge more than a babysitter in the west.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>How many children</strong></span>&nbsp;require care. Babysitting rates vary minimally between the care of 1-3 children of an evening, but will increase&nbsp;if more than 3&nbsp;children require care at the same time.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>Time of day</strong></span>. Many career nannies will tend to lower their hourly rate late at night when it is assumed that the children will be sleeping. For example a career nanny may charge $25p/hour until 8pm, and then $20 per/hour after that. This is common, but not always the case, as they are still being paid for their time and expertise in the event your child should wake.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>Number of hours</strong></span>&nbsp;required. The majority of babysitters will request a&nbsp;minimum of a 3 hour shift&nbsp;for a casual job to make it worth their while. Realistically, you will probably be needing them for more than that anyhow. However, some babysitters may agree to lower their hourly rate for a longer shift. For example, a sitter who charges $20per hour, may sometimes agree to $18 if the shift is longer.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em><span style="font-size:16px">With Sydney being one of the most expensive cities in which to live, its understandable that we try to save money where we can. Lets face it, a night out in Sydney with dinner and drinks can be anywhere from $200 plus...add on your babysitting fees and you could have had a mini-break.</span></em></p>\n\n<p><em><span style="font-size:16px">But,&nbsp;<strong><span style="color:#B22222">there are some things in life we can skimp on, &nbsp;the care of our</span> <span style="color:#B22222">children shouldn&#39;t be one of them.</span>&nbsp;</strong>That&#39;s not to say that the high school girl at the end of your street, who only charges $12 an hour is irresponsible. <span style="color:#B22222">But with age.... comes experience and maturity...</span>.. that&#39;s a given.</span></em></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#006400">&quot;But my baby will be asleep the whole time&quot;</span>, I hear mums say. Is this 100% guaranteed? <span style="color:#006400">If your baby wakes, and experiences distress, will your babysitter know how to deal with him/her? </span>Can she resettle the baby? What if your baby has a febrile convulsion...will the babysitters be able to deal with it?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Chances are, your baby will stay sleeping..but in the event they don&#39;t, wouldn&#39;t you prefer to enjoy your night out knowing they are in experienced and capable hands.</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">The&nbsp;<span style="color:#B22222">National minimum adult wage&nbsp;is $16.87p/hour</span> based on a 38 hour week, &nbsp;plus 25 percent for casual loading equating to $21.10p/hr before tax. Babysitting jobs are almost always a cash agreement, so based on this rate, anything below $15 for an adult to babysit is unethical.</span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="font-size:16px">BELOW IS A GUIDE TO ASSIST PARENTS IN EQUATING A FAIR HOURLY RATE TO PAY THEIR CHOSEN BABYSITTER BASED ON THEIR INDIVIDUAL NEEDS.&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\n\n<p><br />\n<span style="font-size:16px"><span style="color:#B22222"><strong>PLEASE NOTE, THIS IS A GUIDE ONLY!!!</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<div style="margin: 0px;">\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Start with a base rate of $15 per hour&nbsp;</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">add $1 for first aid training (this is very IMPORTANT)</span></p>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">add $1 for child care qualifications&nbsp;</span></p>\n</div>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">add $1 for&nbsp;WWC&nbsp;or police check</span></p>\n</div>\n\n<div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times; line-height: normal;">\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">add $1 for any added child care related expertise (e.g.. anaphylactic training/sleep settling course, etc)</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">add $.50 for every year of experience up to a minimum of 10 years (babysitting and/or nanny work)</span></p>\n\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:16px">Using this guide:</span></strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">&nbsp;Babysitter 1: For $15, you can secure the 16year old neighbours daughter who does not have any formal training or child care related experience.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">Babysitter 2: For $20p/hr...you can secure a babysitter with first aid training, police check, early childhood degree and 4 years experience working with children.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:16px">You my be lucky to get the second babysitter at the first sitters rate, but more often than not, its a case &nbsp;of &#39;you get what you pay for&#39;.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:22px"><span style="color:#0000CD"><strong>A child-free night out in the knowledge your most precious assets are in good hands...PRICELESS!!!</strong></span></span></p>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', 'how-much-should-i-pay-my-babysitter', '2015-03-13');
